Factors that affect the Loan Outcome Status¶

by Suki Chang¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 77,557 loan data in the dataset with 12 features (borrower APR, Prosper score, total inquiries, bank card credit, loan status, term and etc).

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested to find out the factors that will affect the status of the loan.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I would expect the Prosper score will have large impact on loan status. The higher the Prosper score, the higher the probability that a loan will be completed. Also, monthly income, debt-to-income ratio, loan original amount, employment status and homeowner will probably have some impact on the loan outcome.

Univariate Exploration¶

Let's start our analysis with exploring each features in our dataset.

In [15]:
n_listing = loan.shape[0]
listing_counts = loan['LoanStatus'].value_counts()

plt.figure(figsize=[8,4])
sns.countplot(data=loan, x='LoanStatus', color=base_color, order=loan['LoanStatus'].value_counts().index)
plt.xlabel('Loan Status')
plt.title('Loan Status Count')
locs, labels = plt.xticks(rotation=0)

for loc, label in zip(locs, labels): 
    count=listing_counts[label.get_text()]
    pct_string = '{:0.1f}%'.format(100*count/n_listing)
    
    plt.text(loc, count+2, pct_string, ha='center', va = 'bottom', color='black');

So, we can see 67.9% of the loan is current loan and around 20,000 loans have been completed. The high risk loan is about 5,000 or 9.3%.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Total Inquiries¶
  • The distribution is heavily skewed to the right and it is due to the outliers. I removed the values above 30, since only 73 data with total inquiries of 30 and above.
Available Bankcard Credit¶
  • The distribution is heavily skewed to the right and it is due to the outliers. I removed the values above 200K, since only 40 data with credit of 200K and above.
Stated Monthly Income¶
  • The distribution is heavily skewed to the right and it is due to the outliers. I removed the values above 30K, since only 79 data with monthly income of 30K and above.
Stated Monthly Income¶
  • The distribution is heavily skewed to the right and it is due to the outliers. I removed the values above 1.25.

def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating box plots with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    default_color = sns.color_palette()[0]
    sns.boxplot(x, y, color = default_color)
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)

Observations from the above:¶

Loan Status¶
  • APR for high risk is significantly higher than other 2 groups.
  • Prosper Score for high risk group is lower.
  • Total Inquiries for high risk group is slightly higher.
  • Bank Credit and Monthly income are slightly lower for high risk group compared with other 2 groups.
  • Loan amount of current group is the highest, but this could be due to the huge number of people in the 'Current' group.
  • Debt-to-income ratio for completed group is slightly lower.
Employment Status¶
  • APR for full time and employed group is lower compared to others.
  • Prosper Score for self-employed group is the lowest.
  • Total inquiries and bankcard credit look the same across all the groups.
  • Monthly income of the employed group is slightly higher than others.
  • Loan amount for part-time group is the lowest and employed group is the highest.
  • Part-timers have slightly higher debt-to-income ratio
Homeowner¶
  • APR for homeowner is slightly higher than not-a-homeowner.
  • However, the ownership of home does not affect the Prosper score and debt-to-income ratio.
  • Total inquiries, bankcard credit, monthly income and loan amount of homeowners are slightly higher.
Term¶
  • Loan amount and debt-to-income ratio increase as the term increases.
  • There are no significant observations for other features.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

The feature of interest in this dataset is the loan status. Some of the relationships observed are:-

  • Borrower APR of high risk group is significantly higher than the 'Current' and 'Completed. And the 'Current' group enjoys the lowest APR.
  • Not surprisingly, the Prosper score for high risk group is the highest.
  • Additionally, high risk group has lower available bankcard credit and monthly income.
  • The range of the loan amount of current group is the widest, but this could be due to the huge number of people in the 'Current' group.
  • Debt-to-income ratio for completed group is slightly lower.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Some interesting relationships between other features observed:-

  • Borrower APR and Prosper score has a negative correlation, which implies the higher the Prosper score, the lower the APR.
  • Borrower APR and bankcard credit is negative correlated. This means that the APR will be brought down if the borrower has high available bankcard credit.
  • The loan original amount has negative relationship with borrower APR.
  • The Prosper score is postively correlated with available bankcard credit. This implies that the higher the bankcard credit, the higher the Prosper score and the person may enjoy low APR.
  • Loan original amount is positively correlated with stated monthly income.

So from our multivariate analysis, we conclude the followings:-

  • The Prosper score for the high risk group is between 2.0 to 7.0.
  • The borrower APR for high risk group is generally higher, at around 0.25% to 0.4%.

  • The high risk group usually borrows an amount of not more than 15,000 dollar.
  • The high risk group generally earns a monthly income of not more than 10,000 dollar.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

While exploring the relationship between Prosper Score, Homeowner and Loan status, we noticed that:-

For Current Group

  • Homeowner has higher Prosper score than not a homeowner.
  • Not-a-homeowner's Prosper score is almost equal to high risk not-a-homeowner.

High Risk Group

  • Homeowner has the lowest Prosper score among all.

Completed Group

  • The Prosper score is almost the same regardless of the homeownership.

Surprisingly we found that for not-a-homeowner, the Prosper score is almost the same for both current and high risk group. And the Prosper score of these 2 group is even higher than high risk homeowner.
